content: 4. ever since i observed this phenomenon i'm realizing it's a very persistent problem, a trap that's very easy to fall into. there's an interesting paradox(?) where we're *impulsive* + yet living mostly either in an imagined past or future rather than now https://t.co/kmcmodjhg1

in the secular world, morality consists largely of fulfilling our obligations to others, & we have a stubborn tendency to imagine those obligations as debts. ascetic monks might escape it, but the rest of us appear condemned to live in a universe that doesn’t make a lot of sense.
interesting, i remember thinking that it wouldn’t do well. i have some sort of systemic mainstream-blindness and it makes me make inaccurate predictions (eg “beto will win”) https://t.co/3mhorv4n1x

for us, humor is central to keeping things interesting, fun, compelling. you’re not going to escape pain, but if you can laugh about it together (caveat: not contemptuously at each other) then it’s still fun https://t.co/pyg4tg0aou

i believe there are similar-ish insights in other sorts of networks and systems about points-of-failure and robustness. there's something similarly interesting going on with tcp/ip and the layers of abstraction – it's all designed to work in despite failure, isn't it? https://t.co/fnzhnsx3wf

omm: i had an interesting conversation a few days ago where someone was asking me to explain why i'm doing such a soulless-seeming thing like @1000wordvomits – and i felt a little bit trapped because it felt like being asked to explain "why do you love your wife"

i find it interesting i haven’t seen any commentaries extrapolating from criticisms of the wealthy and powerful to criticisms of god, or perhaps inversely how the ultra-wealthy might use religious-sounding justifications for their... outlook? configuration(s)?

if you want cool and interesting jobs that pay decently, you have to be a cool and interesting person that can demonstrably create value. how fucked up is it that our education systems don’t actually optimise for this - and in fact disincentivize this? the game is rigged.

and that's it

people have been indoctrinated to think “smart” is “good” and “dumb” is “bad”. it might seem that way but i gets more complicated than that in practice. you have to risk dumb to do  almost anything interesting. smart then can become a trap https://t.co/sfdvqyrqfe https://t.co/pa8j89oxbl

it's an interesting trap that people set, and i think very few people do it consciously. the most powerful agents of this force are almost blissfully unaware of the role that they play. they don't see the theatre or the stage. which makes them a+ actors

interesting thing to me is that so many people seem to get social-media-famous in a way that doesn’t seem particularly useful or compelling. i think that happens when you fall into the trap of getting addicted to growth for growth’s sake. i experienced that myself as a blogger

rich kids are so often so boring

i suspect that inherited wealth often disincentivizes the pursuit of deep interestingness, by trapping these kids in cheap (to them) validation loops https://t.co/hgom71chj0

@dhaber many japanese bigco did math like “wait why are we leaking margin on financial services when our own employee base is large enough to bootstrap e.g. an insurance company”, which is how my life insurance is now through sony.

frequent other additions: bank, payment processor, etc.

@amyhoy such an interesting comparison with our patch of bootstrapperdom, where "ok you're going to put pedal to the metal for n months with sweat equity and maybe make a few tens of thousands of dollars" sounds great but where you don't follow it with "price of entry: $90k loan @ 12%."

@david_doswell i had vaguely live-and-let-lose sympathies regarding the accredited investor rules when i was younger, but then i saw what crypto specifically did with them: it created optimized predation machines designed to extract the maximum amount of money from retail w/o value creation.

@raganwald @lrz additionally, while i have some reservations about the degree to which professional accreditation is designed to and has the effect of excluding some people from industry, i feel sort of obligated to say that some of us can point to paperwork exceeding any bar set here.

@austenallred i think it is literally designed to be negative. if i dig into individuals feeds i get the "so here's an interesting challenge we had at work this week" thread i came here to read. four likes. but my timeline is "person you follow liked this ill-informed zinger. 32k rt"
https://t.co/jhe7syfoto is an interesting idea to uniquely identify all global locations with three words. i live in exit.escape.unhappy.

@smtuffy i have already read new “this bank is under pressure for idiosyncratic reasons” takes and wonder when people are going to realize that the plural of “idiosyncratic reasons” is “systemic reasons.”

not naming it because i don’t want to look like i’m doomcasting either that banks or banks in general, but, to the extent understanding the financial system matters, the problems from last year are systemic and there has not been a $x00 billion recapitalization to solve them.

that would be a pretty gobsmacking statement about an operating financial institution, but binance has no interest in binance us being an operating financial institution. it is designed to firewall the largest money laundering operation in history from regulatory scrutiny.

“how come people who don’t negotiate get systemically worse rates than people who do?”

the interest rate spread is…

“how come companies negotiate more than retail and banks give them more latitude in doing so?”

the interest rate spread is…

hmm, north dimension certainly seems to be an ftx alter ego designed to launder funds through the u.s. banking system while purporting to engage in proprietary trading, market making, and otc.

where have we seen this group use that same pretext to move $x0 billion before? https://t.co/hjuelt4yba

i would note that bank ceos of systemically important institutions in the us will also never under any circumstances say “we are seeing a higher interest in yen from our customers than we can actually satisfy but we are sure the banking issues with our partners will improve soon”

@byrnehobart (this ridiculously attractive product is designed to get upwardly mobile professionals’ core deposit business and keep it forever. base offering is $100k unsecured line of credit with 2 years of interest only payments and then a 5-10 year amortization with interest rate below 3%)

this is something i didn't appreciate prior to working in the industry, when i ran saas companies.

"why are they so happy to give me more cards but won't approve any signature loans? aren't those basically the same thing?"

nope! ccs are systemically better for banks.
